{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17597941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17597941"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:30:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:30:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15435"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15435"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.34,0.37,0.21,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8126"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69808"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8126"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19705"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69808"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDiarrhoeal illness can be caused by several pathotypes of \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E, each with a distinct mechanism of disease. Some types share similarities with other bacterial pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pathotypes of \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E shares its cellular invasion mechanism with \u003Cem\u003EShigella\u003C/em\u003E species?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enteropathogenic E. coli","Enterotoxigenic E. coli","Enterohaemorrhagic E. coli","Enteroinvasive E. coli","Enteroaggregative E. coli"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnteroinvasive E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E (EIEC) invades and replicates within intestinal epithelial cells, similar to \u003Cem\u003EShigella\u003C/em\u003E species, causing dysentery. Both organisms carry virulence plasmids encoding similar invasion genes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other pathotypes have distinct mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnteropathogenic E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E (EPEC) causes attaching and effacing lesions on intestinal cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterotoxigenic E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E (ETEC) produces heat-labile and heat-stable toxins causing watery diarrhoea\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterohaemorrhagic E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E (EHEC) produces Shiga-like toxins leading to bloody diarrhoea\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnteroaggregative E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E (EAEC) adheres to intestinal mucosa in a characteristic \u0027stacked brick\u0027 pattern\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe genetic similarity between EIEC and \u003Cem\u003EShigella\u003C/em\u003E is so close that some consider them to be the same species.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Enteroinvasive Escherichia coli (EIEC) causes dysentery by invading intestinal cells similar to Shigella species","Different pathotypes of E. coli cause distinct patterns of gastrointestinal disease through unique virulence mechanisms","EIEC and Shigella are so closely related that they are considered the same species by some taxonomists"],"references":["Mueller M, Tainter CR. Escherichia coli Infection. [Updated 2023 Jul 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564298/","Sell J, Dolan B. Common Gastrointestinal Infections. Prim Care. 2018 Sep;45(3):519-532. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.05.008. Epub 2018 Jul 9. PMID: 30115338","Burd EM, Hinrichs BH. Gastrointestinal Infections. Molecular Pathology in Clinical Practice. 2015 May 19:707\u201334. doi: 10.1007/978-3-319-19674-9_50. PMCID: PMC7123654","Kotloff KL. Bacterial diarrhoea. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2022 Apr 1;34(2):147-155. doi: 10.1097/MOP.0000000000001107. PMID: 35165210","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15435"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T19:51:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T19:53:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8126"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69808"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","link